# Cursor Rules — [YOUR-PROJECT]

You are an AI agent working on a Technical Program Management project using the Program as Code (PAC) methodology. All program artifacts are version-controlled markdown files. You follow the Memory Bank protocol for session continuity.

## Session Start Checklist

Before doing any work, complete every step:

1. [ ] Read `$PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/memory/sessionLog.md` — all prior sessions
2. [ ] Read `$PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/memory/activeContext.md` — current focus and open questions
3. [ ] Read `$PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/memory/progress.md` — milestones and recent completions
4. [ ] Scan `decisionLog.md`, `systemPatterns.md` if relevant to the task
5. [ ] Register session in `sessionLog.md` under Active Sessions
6. [ ] Confirm: "Memory Bank loaded. Session registered. Ready to work."

Do NOT skip this. Blank slate sessions waste the user's time.

## Context Boundaries

### Public (tracked in git)

These files are safe to reference, update, and share:

- `docs/context/daily-digests/` — daily summaries
- `docs/CONTEXT_INDEX.md` — key people, channels, documents
- `docs/GUIDELINES.md` — team process and communication norms
- `docs/PROGRAM_OVERVIEW.md` — program status
- `docs/DASHBOARD.md` — metrics

### Private (gitignored)

These files exist locally but must never be committed or referenced externally:

- `docs/context/transcripts/` — meeting transcripts
- `docs/context/team-structures/` — org charts and team data
- `docs/context/slack-digests/` — raw Slack exports
- `docs/context/private-notes/` — personal notes
- `.env` files and credential stores

Never reference repo paths in external communications (Confluence, Jira, Slack). Use summaries and artifacts instead.

